description: Borrowed from Latin satiatus, past participle of satiare (“to fill full, satiate”), from satis (“sufficient”).

adjectives.description: satiate (comparative more satiate, superlative most satiate)

entries.meaning: Filled to satisfaction or to excess.

verbs.description: satiate (third-person singular simple present satiates, present participle satiating, simple past and past participle satiated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To fill to satisfaction; to satisfy.
examples: Nothing seemed to satiate her desire for knowledge.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To satisfy to excess. To fill to satiety.
